Arkansas River - Random Forest Testing on GDE Plant Functional Groups

Matthew Lurtz

2025-11-21

Science Question

The main goal in this manuscript is to test if a given plant functional group (e.g., response variable, NDVI derived from Planet Imagery) has a stronger correlation or dependence with a specific hydroclimatic variable (e.g., covariate, groundwater depth or rainfall, or temperature, etc.). Notably, we will also test if this dependence changes with respect to the temporal resolution (i.e., daily, weekly, and monthly) at which we regress the covariates on the response variable and how the dependence changes during wet and dry years.

Data and Methods

Bring in Y and X Datasets (Daily, Populus fremontii)

Figure 1. Daily observations of the response variable and select covariates: (a) standardized NDVI, and (b) averages or summations of precipitation, discharge, depth to groundwater (C1), and average atmospheric temperature all plotted on a standarized scale. There are interesting patterns in the peak months of the NDVI time series for years 2018, 2020, and 2022. The time series of the groundwater data is the most sparse of all covariates (5-14-18 to 10-17-20, 10-25-23 to 6-26-25)

Deseasonalize NDVI using Dynamic Harmonic Regression (Monthly-Weekly-Daily, Populus fremontii)

Figure 2. Output from deseasonalizing the response data using a Bayesian implementation of the dynamic harmonic regression model (i.e., one harmonic plus autoregressive component) at monthly, weekly and daily time resolutions: (a) posterior distribution of the AR(1) correlation coefficient at the daily, weekly, and monthly resolution for the phreatophyte PFG, and (b,c,d) an ACF plot of the daily, weekly, and monthly deseasonlized NDVI time series with lag up to 1-year.

Wet and Dry Years, Ranked

Figure 3. Monthly summarizations of covariates (solid lines) plotted against month-specific median and 95 percentiles (dashed, colored lines): (a) average monthly discharge (cms), and (b) monthly totals of precipitation minus evapotranspiration (alfalfa reference, mm). Discharge shows 2017 and 2018 as above average and P-ET shows simultaneously that 2018 is very dry early on in the year (April) and then wetter than average during peak season (May, June) but 2019 and 2021 years each have multiple months drier than the median.

Figure 4. Water year totals for precipitation, evapotranspiration and discharge for the period of interest.

OOS model validation, using 25 percent of original dataset, for all PFGs at monthly, weekly, and daily temporal resolutions with a 1:1 (red-dashed) line plot and a regression (color by PFG) line to highlight predictive accuracy and bias of the witheld (i.e., testing) dataset: a) monthly, b) weekly, and c) daily.

Figure 5. Top 5 features of importance based on impurity: a) monthly, b) weekly, and c) daily. This Impurity is based on the average total reduction of the loss function for a given feature across all trees. Reference: (https://bradleyboehmke.github.io/HOML/random-forest.html).
